  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT327-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">kiḻavaṉ kēṭkum aṇmaiyaṉāka avaṉ malaiyiṉ iṉṟu ukuvarum yāṟṟiṟku uraippāḷāy
          uraittatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by her as if telling [something] to the river,
          which comes dropping from his mountain, while HE is near [enough] to hear. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT327">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> nalkiṉ vāḻu nalkūrn tōrvayi</l>
          <l> ṉayaṉila rākuta ṉaṉṟeṉa vuṇarnta</l>
          <l> kuṉṟa nāṭaṉ ṟaṉṉiṉu naṉṟu</l>
          <l> niṉṉilai koṭitāṟ ṟīya kaluḻi</l>
          <l> nammaṉai maṭamaka ḷiṉṉa meṉmaic</l>
          <l> cāyala ḷaḷiya ḷeṉṉāy</l>
          <l> vāḻaitan taṉaiyāṟ cilampupul leṉavē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Your attitude [is] cruel indeed, bad muddy water <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">	kaluḻi </term>: Cām. glosses <term xml:lang="ta"> āṟu </term> "river", but literally it is "muddy water", which is probably a rapid river after the rains.  </note> ,</l>
          <l rend="indent">very, more even than [that of] the man from a land of hills himself,</l>
          <l rend="indent">who realised <note place="foot">What is denoted by  <term xml:lang="ta"> uṇar-tal </term> here? The arising of an insight?      </note> “good [is it] that there are those free from longing,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">for the sake of the poor who live when they are granted</l>
          <l rend="indent8">[something]”<note place="foot"> How precisely to construe this <term xml:lang="ta"> eṉa </term>-clause and what does it mean? In any case it seems to be an aphorism. Is it that men fulfil a social duty when they go abroad in spite of their women in order to make wealth?      </note>.</l>
          <l>Without saying <note place="foot">  <term xml:lang="ta">  eṉṉāy </term> is not absolutive, but either a participial noun 2nd sg. as subject ("as one, that does not say/ consider ... you have ...") or an independent sentence.   </note> “the inexperienced daughter in our house</l>
          <l rend="indent5">[is] of such soft grace, she [is] pitiable”,</l>
          <l>you have indeed brought banana trees <note place="foot"> What is the point in this accusation? The river has brought a tree/trees from HIS mountain side, but not him?     </note> from the mountain side,</l>
          <l rend="indent8">empty <note place="foot"> How can we integrate <term xml:lang="ta"> pulleṉa </term>? Is it the present state of the mountain side, which resembles her own state?     </note> .</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
